A New Science
This summer, an unusual conference took place in Paris. There, researchers met to think about the necessity of a new science that could be as revolutionary as Einstein's insights a hundred years ago.
The majority of scientists assume that the fundamental questions of the sciences have been answered.
In view of the great challenges, it is believed that there is little left to discover.
The remaining questions can be divided into three groups: First, the major unsolved puzzles of science (such as the unification of gravity and electricity in a theory), whose investigation requires enormous investments and the infrastructure of the First World. Second, data collection, which refers to work related to archaeological excavations and biological/genetic studies, and third, problems whose solutions must be based on scientific principles, such as the fight against AIDS or global warming.
Furthermore, in many places, people believe that the only difficult part of the work would be to use already known natural laws with the help of new technologies for the benefit of humanity.
Who could deny that?
Today's models do work, after all.
However, an increasing group of scientists points to phenomena that are not well explained by today's theories.
These problems do occur more frequently, but they are also skillfully circumvented, because there simply is no science that would explain these problems.
This missing science would describe processes and the emergence of entire systems.
Within the individual scientific disciplines, knowledge is fairly well established.
Physics, at least the part with which we as ordinary people are confronted, is well researched.
Chemistry and biochemistry are also built on solid foundations – although there are still a few things in our body that we do not yet understand, it can be assumed that the basic mechanisms of interaction between cells and molecules are known.
In addition, there are the new social sciences that deal with people and societies.
In each of these areas – physics, biochemistry, and social sciences – the theories are well-established and largely beyond dispute.
Each discipline has its own language and its own mechanisms.
In the rarest cases, a scientist is an expert in more than one field, because these worlds and languages are simply so different.
This means that we cannot find answers to complex questions that require the involvement of multiple disciplines.
Consider, for example, the brain.
This complex organ consists of molecules whose interactions occur based on the principles of physics. The information conveyed is transmitted according to the laws of electricity.
In addition, there is a system of specialized cells that communicate by exchanging chemical substances and also transmit information in this way.
In the interaction between two brains, a new level is added: here, information exchange occurs through language, signs, and images.
At each level, it is about the exchange of information and there are appropriate theories that explain the processes at each individual level.
However, information is also exchanged between the individual levels, but there is no science that could even begin to explain this information exchange.
To compensate for this lack, some scientists have tried to redefine the toolkit for explaining processes within one level in order to then apply it on another level.
These attempts then lead to something like a "language" at the cellular level and "energy" behind organized societies.
Sometimes this "transplantation" of explanatory patterns works quite well, but the fundamental problem is not solved thereby: What is the nature of the information exchanged between the individual levels and how is it transmitted?
Now, almost all systems in this world consist of such levels.
And in all cases, there is this embarrassing lack of knowledge about how the entire system functions.
The group of interdisciplinary scientists who met in Paris has loosely formed under the name "Foundations of Information Science."
The researchers come from different countries and disciplines and have been working together on a decentralized basis for eight years.
Alongside scientists from the relevant disciplines, art theorists, psychiatrists, language experts, and philosophers are also beginning to participate in the discourse.
The majority of the group relies on this "transplantation strategy," in which the scientific foundations of one level are adapted and supplemented and transferred to another.
Others, on the other hand, consider a completely new approach to be necessary.
In their view, many scientific norms are the product of historical accidents and new ways of thinking are necessary.
If the FIS group is lucky, new radical approaches will emerge from scientists who currently have no access to First World infrastructure.
Completely free thinking is an underestimated factor.
Nearly all activities taking place under the banner of "science" have, like their counterparts in the world of economics, developed an institutional character.
It is believed that developing countries would have to build similar resources as industrialized countries. This could however stifle creative thinking.
Many young scientists are currently experiencing a revolution, and many of these – sometimes revolutionary – ideas come from laboratories and research centers that are not associated with the major institutions.
The most thoughtful approaches in the field of mathematical algorithms came for twenty years from the Soviet Union, where there was a lack of computer capacity at every corner.
The most brilliant and literally world-changing insights in the field of physics in the last few decades did not come, as expected, from the known innovation centers, but from Budapest.
In Iran, there is a tradition of architecture that has led cognitive scientists to important insights.
And the most radical new ideas in the field of second-generation artificial intelligence (so-called "autonomous agents") today come from Prague.
The most creative scientific achievements went down in history.
When Einstein expanded physics with a new way of thinking, this changed the identity of space and time. The FIS conference in July was the unexpected beginning of an attempt to redefine the universe in this way.
Those gaps were identified for which explanations must be found.
More scientists from innovative regions will be added to this group, in order to then identify those problems that could be solved once this new science is developed, or discovered, one might say.

